body:
Server Components in React 19 run only on the server and can directly access databases, file systems, and APIs without exposing credentials to the client. They cannot use hooks like useState or useEffect.

```tsx
// app/users/page.tsx — this is a Server Component by default
import { db } from '@/lib/db';

export default async function UsersPage() {
  const users = await db.query.users.findMany({
    orderBy: (users, { desc }) => [desc(users.createdAt)],
    limit: 50,
  });

  return (
    <ul>
      {users.map((user) => (
        <li key={user.id}>{user.name} — {user.email}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

Key rules: Server Components are the default in Next.js App Router. They cannot contain event handlers, browser APIs, or React hooks. To add interactivity, extract a Client Component with `'use client'` and pass server-fetched data as props. Server Components can import Client Components, but not the reverse.

The `useOptimistic` hook lets you show an optimistic state while an async action (like a Server Action) is pending. It reverts automatically if the action fails.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useOptimistic } from 'react';
import { addTodo } from '@/app/actions';

export function TodoList({ todos }: { todos: Todo[] }) {
  const [optimisticTodos, addOptimisticTodo] = useOptimistic(
    todos,
    (state, newTodo: Todo) => [...state, newTodo]
  );

  async function handleAdd(formData: FormData) {
    const title = formData.get('title') as string;
    addOptimisticTodo({ id: crypto.randomUUID(), title, completed: false });
    await addTodo(formData);
  }

  return (
    <form action={handleAdd}>
      <input name="title" required />
      <button type="submit">Add</button>
      <ul>
        {optimisticTodos.map((t) => (
          <li key={t.id}>{t.title}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </form>
  );
}
```

The second argument to `useOptimistic` is a reducer that merges the optimistic value into the current state. When the action completes and the parent re-renders with new `todos`, the optimistic state is replaced.

The `useFormStatus` hook reads the status of a parent `<form>`. It must be called from a component rendered inside the form, not from the component that renders the form itself.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useFormStatus } from 'react-dom';

function SubmitButton() {
  const { pending, data, method, action } = useFormStatus();
  return (
    <button type="submit" disabled={pending}>
      {pending ? 'Saving...' : 'Save'}
    </button>
  );
}

// Usage:
export function MyForm({ saveAction }: { saveAction: (fd: FormData) => Promise<void> }) {
  return (
    <form action={saveAction}>
      <input name="name" required />
      <SubmitButton />
    </form>
  );
}
```

Common mistake: calling `useFormStatus()` in the same component that renders `<form>`. It will always return `{ pending: false }` in that case because the hook looks for a parent form in the React tree, not a sibling. Always extract the submit button into its own component.

The `useActionState` hook (renamed from `useFormState` in React 19) wraps a Server Action to provide previous state, enabling progressive enhancement and validation errors.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useActionState } from 'react';
import { createUser } from '@/app/actions';

type State = { error?: string; success?: boolean };

export function SignupForm() {
  const [state, formAction, isPending] = useActionState(
    createUser,
    { error: undefined, success: false }
  );

  return (
    <form action={formAction}>
      <input name="email" type="email" required />
      <input name="password" type="password" required />
      {state.error && <p className="text-red-500">{state.error}</p>}
      {state.success && <p className="text-green-500">Account created!</p>}
      <button disabled={isPending}>
        {isPending ? 'Creating...' : 'Sign Up'}
      </button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

The Server Action must accept `(prevState: State, formData: FormData) => Promise<State>` as its signature. The third return value `isPending` was added in React 19 — it replaces the need for a separate `useFormStatus` in many cases.

Server Actions are async functions that run on the server. They are defined with `'use server'` either at the top of a file or inline in a function body.

```tsx
// app/actions.ts
'use server';

import { db } from '@/lib/db';
import { revalidatePath } from 'next/cache';
import { z } from 'zod';

const schema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1).max(200),
});

export async function createPost(prevState: any, formData: FormData) {
  const parsed = schema.safeParse({
    title: formData.get('title'),
  });

  if (!parsed.success) {
    return { error: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  }

  await db.insert(posts).values({ title: parsed.data.title });
  revalidatePath('/posts');
  return { success: true };
}
```

Server Actions can be passed to `<form action={...}>`, called from event handlers, or invoked from `useActionState`. They support file uploads via `FormData`, can call `redirect()`, and can revalidate cached data. Always validate inputs — Server Actions are public HTTP endpoints under the hood.

Layouts in the App Router wrap child pages and persist across navigations. They receive a `children` prop and do not re-render when navigating between sibling routes.

```tsx
// app/dashboard/layout.tsx
import { Sidebar } from '@/components/sidebar';
import { getUser } from '@/lib/auth';
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';

export default async function DashboardLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  const user = await getUser();
  if (!user) redirect('/login');

  return (
    <div className="flex min-h-screen">
      <Sidebar user={user} />
      <main className="flex-1 p-6">{children}</main>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Key behavior: Layouts are Server Components by default. They do NOT re-render on navigation — React preserves their state. This means you cannot use `searchParams` or `pathname` in layouts (use `useSearchParams()` in a Client Component child instead). Each route segment can have its own layout, and they nest automatically. The root layout (`app/layout.tsx`) must contain `<html>` and `<body>` tags.

A `loading.tsx` file in any route segment automatically wraps the page in a React Suspense boundary, showing a fallback while the page's async data loads.

```tsx
// app/dashboard/loading.tsx
export default function DashboardLoading() {
  return (
    <div className="animate-pulse space-y-4 p-6">
      <div className="h-8 w-48 rounded bg-gray-200" />
      <div className="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        {Array.from({ length: 6 }).map((_, i) => (
          <div key={i} className="h-32 rounded bg-gray-200" />
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This is equivalent to wrapping your page with `<Suspense fallback={<DashboardLoading />}>`. The loading state shows instantly on navigation while the Server Component fetches data. For more granular control, use `<Suspense>` boundaries directly inside your page to stream in sections independently. The loading file applies to `page.tsx` in the same segment and all nested child segments unless they define their own `loading.tsx`.

An `error.tsx` file creates a React error boundary that catches errors in its route segment and all child segments, preventing the entire app from crashing.

```tsx
'use client'; // Error boundaries must be Client Components

import { useEffect } from 'react';

export default function DashboardError({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.error('Dashboard error:', error);
    // Send to error tracking service
  }, [error]);

  return (
    <div className="rounded-lg border border-red-200 bg-red-50 p-6">
      <h2 className="text-lg font-semibold text-red-800">Something went wrong</h2>
      <p className="mt-2 text-red-600">{error.message}</p>
      <button
        onClick={reset}
        className="mt-4 rounded bg-red-600 px-4 py-2 text-white"
      >
        Try again
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The `reset` function re-renders the error boundary's children without a full page reload. The `digest` property is a hash generated by Next.js for server-side errors — the actual error message is not sent to the client in production. `error.tsx` does NOT catch errors in `layout.tsx` of the same segment — use `global-error.tsx` for the root layout.

Parallel routes let you render multiple pages in the same layout simultaneously using named slots. Slots are defined with the `@folder` convention.

```
app/dashboard/
  layout.tsx
  page.tsx
  @analytics/page.tsx
  @analytics/loading.tsx
  @team/page.tsx
  @team/default.tsx
```

```tsx
// app/dashboard/layout.tsx
export default function DashboardLayout({
  children,
  analytics,
  team,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  analytics: React.ReactNode;
  team: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  return (
    <div>
      <div>{children}</div>
      <div className="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div>{analytics}</div>
        <div>{team}</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Each slot can have its own `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, and nested routes. A `default.tsx` file is required for slots that may not match the current URL — it defines the fallback content. Parallel routes are useful for dashboards, modals, and conditional rendering based on auth state. Each slot streams independently.

Next.js provides two functions for invalidating cached data after mutations: `revalidatePath` for route-based and `revalidateTag` for tag-based invalidation.

```tsx
// app/actions.ts
'use server';

import { revalidatePath, revalidateTag } from 'next/cache';

export async function updatePost(id: string, formData: FormData) {
  await db.update(posts).set({ title: formData.get('title') as string }).where(eq(posts.id, id));

  // Option 1: Revalidate a specific path
  revalidatePath('/posts');
  revalidatePath(`/posts/${id}`);

  // Option 2: Revalidate by tag (more granular)
  revalidateTag('posts');
  revalidateTag(`post-${id}`);
}

// Using tags with fetch:
async function getPost(id: string) {
  const res = await fetch(`https://api.example.com/posts/${id}`, {
    next: { tags: [`post-${id}`, 'posts'] },
  });
  return res.json();
}
```

`revalidatePath('/')` revalidates everything. `revalidatePath('/posts', 'layout')` revalidates the layout and all pages below it. Tags are more surgical — they only invalidate fetches that were tagged with that specific string. Prefer tags over paths for fine-grained control. Both functions only mark data as stale; the actual re-fetch happens on the next request.

In Next.js App Router, `fetch()` in Server Components is cached by default. This catches many developers off guard when they expect fresh data on every request.

```tsx
// This response is cached indefinitely by default (static rendering)
const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');

// To opt out of caching entirely:
const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  cache: 'no-store',
});

// To revalidate every 60 seconds (ISR-style):
const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  next: { revalidate: 60 },
});

// To tag for on-demand revalidation:
const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  next: { tags: ['my-data'] },
});
```

Note: In Next.js 15, the default changed — `fetch` is no longer cached by default (you must opt in with `cache: 'force-cache'`). If you are on Next.js 14, add `cache: 'no-store'` or `export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic'` to get fresh data. For non-fetch data sources (like direct DB queries), use `unstable_cache` or the `connection()` function to control caching behavior.

Error message: `Error: Text content does not match server-rendered HTML. Warning: Text content did not match. Server: "..." Client: "..."`

This occurs when the HTML generated on the server differs from what React renders on the client during hydration.

```tsx
// BAD — causes hydration mismatch
export default function Page() {
  return <p>Current time: {new Date().toLocaleTimeString()}</p>; // Different on server vs client
}

// BAD — nesting <div> inside <p>
export default function Page() {
  return <p><div>Invalid HTML nesting</div></p>;
}

// FIX 1 — use useEffect for client-only values
'use client';
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

export function Clock() {
  const [time, setTime] = useState<string | null>(null);
  useEffect(() => {
    setTime(new Date().toLocaleTimeString());
  }, []);
  return <p>Current time: {time ?? 'Loading...'}</p>;
}

// FIX 2 — suppress hydration warning when intentional
<time suppressHydrationWarning>{new Date().toISOString()}</time>
```

Common causes: using `Date.now()`, `Math.random()`, browser-only APIs like `window.innerWidth`, different locales between server and client, and browser extensions modifying the DOM. Invalid HTML nesting (e.g., `<div>` inside `<p>`) also causes this.

Error message: `You're importing a component that needs server-only. That only works in a Server Component but one of its parents is marked with "use client", so it's a Client Component.`

This happens when a Client Component (or its dependency tree) imports code that can only run on the server.

```tsx
// lib/db.ts
import 'server-only'; // Marks this module as server-only
import { drizzle } from 'drizzle-orm/neon-http';
export const db = drizzle(process.env.DATABASE_URL!);

// components/UserList.tsx
'use client';
import { db } from '@/lib/db'; // ERROR! Can't import server-only in client

// FIX: Pass data as props from a Server Component
// app/users/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { db } from '@/lib/db';
import { UserList } from '@/components/UserList';

export default async function UsersPage() {
  const users = await db.query.users.findMany();
  return <UserList users={users} />;
}

// components/UserList.tsx
'use client';
export function UserList({ users }: { users: User[] }) {
  // Now uses serializable props, no server imports
  return <ul>{users.map(u => <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>)}</ul>;
}
```

The `'use client'` directive creates a boundary. Everything imported into that file becomes part of the client bundle. Use the `server-only` package to get clear error messages instead of subtle runtime failures.

Error message: `Type '() => { title: string; }' is not assignable to type '(props: ...) => Promise<Metadata> | Metadata'.`

The metadata API in Next.js App Router has specific type requirements that can cause confusing TypeScript errors.

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

// Static metadata — use export const
export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'My Page',
  description: 'Page description',
};

// Dynamic metadata — export an async function
export async function generateMetadata({
  params,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
}): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { slug } = await params; // In Next.js 15, params is a Promise
  const post = await getPost(slug);

  return {
    title: post.title,
    description: post.excerpt,
    openGraph: {
      title: post.title,
      images: [post.coverImage],
    },
  };
}
```

Common mistakes: (1) Exporting both `metadata` and `generateMetadata` in the same file — only one is allowed. (2) In Next.js 15, `params` and `searchParams` are now Promises — you must `await` them. (3) Using `generateMetadata` in a `'use client'` file — metadata generation only works in Server Components. (4) Forgetting to type the return as `Promise<Metadata>`.

`React.memo` wraps a component so it only re-renders when its props change (shallow comparison). Essential for expensive list items and charts.

```tsx
import { memo } from 'react';

interface DataRowProps {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  value: number;
  onUpdate: (id: string, value: number) => void;
}

export const DataRow = memo(function DataRow({ id, name, value, onUpdate }: DataRowProps) {
  console.log(`Rendering DataRow ${id}`);
  return (
    <tr>
      <td>{name}</td>
      <td>{value}</td>
      <td>
        <button onClick={() => onUpdate(id, value + 1)}>+1</button>
      </td>
    </tr>
  );
});

// With custom comparison:
export const ExpensiveChart = memo(
  function ExpensiveChart({ data, config }: ChartProps) {
    return <canvas ref={renderChart(data, config)} />;
  },
  (prevProps, nextProps) => {
    return prevProps.data.length === nextProps.data.length
      && prevProps.config.type === nextProps.config.type;
  }
);
```

Important: `React.memo` only prevents re-renders from parent updates. If the component uses `useContext`, it will still re-render when the context value changes. Also, if you pass a new function or object reference as a prop on every render, memo is useless — combine with `useCallback`/`useMemo`.

Use `useMemo` to memoize computed values and `useCallback` to memoize functions, preventing unnecessary re-renders of `memo`-wrapped children.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useMemo, useCallback, useState } from 'react';
import { DataTable } from './DataTable'; // wrapped in React.memo

export function Dashboard({ items }: { items: Item[] }) {
  const [search, setSearch] = useState('');
  const [sortKey, setSortKey] = useState<'name' | 'date'>('name');

  // useMemo: recompute only when items, search, or sortKey change
  const filteredItems = useMemo(() => {
    const filtered = items.filter((item) =>
      item.name.toLowerCase().includes(search.toLowerCase())
    );
    return filtered.sort((a, b) => a[sortKey].localeCompare(b[sortKey]));
  }, [items, search, sortKey]);

  // useCallback: stable function reference
  const handleDelete = useCallback(async (id: string) => {
    await fetch(`/api/items/${id}`, { method: 'DELETE' });
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <input value={search} onChange={(e) => setSearch(e.target.value)} />
      <DataTable items={filteredItems} onDelete={handleDelete} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Don't overuse these hooks — they have overhead. Only memoize when: (1) passing values to `memo`-wrapped children, (2) values are expensive to compute, or (3) values are dependencies of other hooks. The React compiler (React 19+) auto-memoizes, reducing the need for manual memoization.

Zustand is a lightweight state management library that works well with Next.js App Router. It avoids the provider-wrapping pattern and has a simple API.

```tsx
// stores/useCartStore.ts
import { create } from 'zustand';
import { persist } from 'zustand/middleware';

interface CartItem {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  quantity: number;
  price: number;
}

interface CartStore {
  items: CartItem[];
  addItem: (item: Omit<CartItem, 'quantity'>) => void;
  removeItem: (id: string) => void;
  total: () => number;
}

export const useCartStore = create<CartStore>()(
  persist(
    (set, get) => ({
      items: [],
      addItem: (item) =>
        set((state) => {
          const existing = state.items.find((i) => i.id === item.id);
          if (existing) {
            return {
              items: state.items.map((i) =>
                i.id === item.id ? { ...i, quantity: i.quantity + 1 } : i
              ),
            };
          }
          return { items: [...state.items, { ...item, quantity: 1 }] };
        }),
      removeItem: (id) =>
        set((state) => ({ items: state.items.filter((i) => i.id !== id) })),
      total: () => get().items.reduce((sum, i) => sum + i.price * i.quantity, 0),
    }),
    { name: 'cart-storage' }
  )
);
```

With `persist` middleware, state survives page refreshes via localStorage. In Next.js, Zustand stores are client-only — use them in `'use client'` components. For SSR hydration, use `zustand/middleware`'s `onRehydrateStorage` to handle mismatches.

TanStack Query manages server state with caching, background refetching, and stale-while-revalidate. Setting it up with Next.js App Router requires a provider in a Client Component.

```tsx
// providers/query-provider.tsx
'use client';
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { useState } from 'react';

export function QueryProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [client] = useState(
    () => new QueryClient({
      defaultOptions: {
        queries: {
          staleTime: 60 * 1000,
          refetchOnWindowFocus: false,
        },
      },
    })
  );
  return <QueryClientProvider client={client}>{children}</QueryClientProvider>;
}

// hooks/useUsers.ts
import { useQuery, useMutation, useQueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';

export function useUsers() {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['users'],
    queryFn: async () => {
      const res = await fetch('/api/users');
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch');
      return res.json() as Promise<User[]>;
    },
  });
}

export function useDeleteUser() {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: (id: string) => fetch(`/api/users/${id}`, { method: 'DELETE' }),
    onSuccess: () => queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['users'] }),
  });
}
```

Add `<QueryProvider>` in your root layout. Use `useState` to create the client (not module-level) to avoid sharing state between requests in SSR.

When a Server Action throws an error, Next.js catches it and only sends a generic error to the client for security. The actual error message is replaced with a digest hash in production.

```tsx
// BAD — throwing errors in Server Actions
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  const result = await db.insert(posts).values({ ... });
  if (!result) throw new Error('DB insert failed'); // Client won't see this message!
}

// GOOD — return errors as data
'use server';
export async function createPost(prevState: any, formData: FormData) {
  try {
    const parsed = schema.safeParse(Object.fromEntries(formData));
    if (!parsed.success) {
      return { success: false, error: 'Validation failed', fieldErrors: parsed.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
    }
    await db.insert(posts).values(parsed.data);
    revalidatePath('/posts');
    return { success: true, error: null };
  } catch (e) {
    return { success: false, error: 'Failed to create post. Please try again.' };
  }
}
```

Pattern: return a discriminated union `{ success: boolean; error?: string }` from Server Actions instead of throwing. Use `useActionState` to consume the returned state. Only use `throw` when you want the error boundary to catch it (e.g., for truly unexpected errors).

Choosing between Server and Client Components is one of the most important decisions in Next.js App Router.

```
| Use Case                          | Server Component | Client Component |
|-----------------------------------|------------------|------------------|
| Fetch data from DB/API            | Yes              | No (use hooks)   |
| Access backend resources           | Yes              | No               |
| Keep secrets (API keys, tokens)   | Yes              | No               |
| Reduce client JS bundle           | Yes              | No               |
| Use useState/useEffect            | No               | Yes              |
| Use event handlers (onClick)      | No               | Yes              |
| Use browser APIs (window, etc)    | No               | Yes              |
| Use React context                 | No               | Yes              |
| Use custom hooks with state       | No               | Yes              |
```

Best practice: default to Server Components. Only add `'use client'` when you need interactivity. Push `'use client'` boundaries as far down the tree as possible — wrap only the interactive leaf component, not the entire page.

```tsx
// Server Component (page)
export default async function ProductPage({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const product = await getProduct(id);
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{product.name}</h1>
      <p>{product.description}</p>
      <AddToCartButton productId={id} /> {/* Only this is 'use client' */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

In Next.js 15, `params` and `searchParams` in page components, layouts, and `generateMetadata` are now `Promise` objects. This is a breaking change from Next.js 14.

```tsx
// Next.js 14 (old way)
export default function Page({ params }: { params: { slug: string } }) {
  return <h1>{params.slug}</h1>; // Direct access
}

// Next.js 15 (new way) — must await
export default async function Page({
  params,
}: {
  params: Promise<{ slug: string }>;
}) {
  const { slug } = await params;
  return <h1>{slug}</h1>;
}

// Same for searchParams:
export default async function SearchPage({
  searchParams,
}: {
  searchParams: Promise<{ q?: string; page?: string }>;
}) {
  const { q, page } = await searchParams;
  const results = await search(q, Number(page) || 1);
  return <SearchResults results={results} />;
}
```

This change enables Next.js to start rendering the page shell before the params are available (from the URL parsing pipeline). The codemod `npx @next/codemod@latest next-async-request-api .` can auto-migrate most cases. If you see `TypeError: Cannot read properties of Promise`, this is likely the cause.

Key configuration options for Next.js App Router projects in `next.config.js` (or `.mjs`/`.ts`).

```ts
// next.config.ts
import type { NextConfig } from 'next';

const config: NextConfig = {
  // Enable React strict mode
  reactStrictMode: true,

  // Image optimization
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      { protocol: 'https', hostname: '**.example.com' },
    ],
  },

  // Server Actions config
  serverActions: {
    bodySizeLimit: '2mb',
    allowedOrigins: ['my-app.com'],
  },

  // Redirect and rewrite rules
  async redirects() {
    return [
      { source: '/old-path', destination: '/new-path', permanent: true },
    ];
  },

  // Environment variables exposed to the browser
  env: {
    NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL: process.env.API_URL,
  },

  // Turbopack (dev only, stable in Next.js 15)
  // Run with: next dev --turbopack

  // Output standalone for Docker
  output: 'standalone',

  // Customize webpack (only if needed)
  webpack: (config, { isServer }) => {
    if (!isServer) {
      config.resolve.fallback = { fs: false };
    }
    return config;
  },
};

export default config;
```

Next.js 15 supports `next.config.ts` natively (no extra setup). The `output: 'standalone'` option creates a self-contained build that includes only needed dependencies, ideal for Docker deployments.

Error message: `Error: Event handlers cannot be passed to Client Component props.
  <button onClick={function onClick}>
                   ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
If you need interactivity, consider converting part of this to a Client Component.`

This error occurs when you try to use event handlers like `onClick` in a Server Component.

```tsx
// BAD — Server Components can't have event handlers
export default function Page() {
  return (
    <button onClick={() => console.log('clicked')}>Click me</button>
  );
}

// FIX — Extract interactive part to a Client Component
// components/Counter.tsx
'use client';
import { useState } from 'react';

export function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(c => c + 1)}>
      Count: {count}
    </button>
  );
}

// app/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { Counter } from '@/components/Counter';

export default function Page() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>My Page</h1>
      <Counter />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Remember: functions are not serializable, so they cannot cross the server-to-client boundary as props. The only exception is Server Actions (functions with `'use server'`), which can be passed as `action` props to forms.

Zustand re-renders components whenever any part of the store changes by default. Use selectors to subscribe to only the state slices you need.

```tsx
import { create } from 'zustand';
import { useShallow } from 'zustand/react/shallow';

interface AppStore {
  user: { name: string; email: string } | null;
  theme: 'light' | 'dark';
  notifications: Notification[];
  setTheme: (theme: 'light' | 'dark') => void;
  addNotification: (n: Notification) => void;
}

const useAppStore = create<AppStore>()((set) => ({
  user: null,
  theme: 'light',
  notifications: [],
  setTheme: (theme) => set({ theme }),
  addNotification: (n) => set((s) => ({ notifications: [...s.notifications, n] })),
}));

// BAD — re-renders on ANY store change
function Header() {
  const store = useAppStore();
  return <span>{store.user?.name}</span>;
}

// GOOD — re-renders only when user changes
function Header() {
  const user = useAppStore((state) => state.user);
  return <span>{user?.name}</span>;
}

// GOOD — multiple values with shallow comparison
function ThemeToggle() {
  const { theme, setTheme } = useAppStore(
    useShallow((state) => ({ theme: state.theme, setTheme: state.setTheme }))
  );
  return <button onClick={() => setTheme(theme === 'light' ? 'dark' : 'light')}>{theme}</button>;
}
```

Use `useShallow` from `zustand/react/shallow` when selecting multiple values. Without it, the object selector creates a new reference every render, defeating memoization.

You can prefetch TanStack Query data in Server Components and pass it to Client Components via `HydrationBoundary`, avoiding loading spinners on initial render.

```tsx
// app/users/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { dehydrate, HydrationBoundary, QueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { UserList } from './UserList';

export default async function UsersPage() {
  const queryClient = new QueryClient();

  await queryClient.prefetchQuery({
    queryKey: ['users'],
    queryFn: async () => {
      const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/users');
      return res.json();
    },
  });

  return (
    <HydrationBoundary state={dehydrate(queryClient)}>
      <UserList />
    </HydrationBoundary>
  );
}

// app/users/UserList.tsx
'use client';
import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';

export function UserList() {
  const { data: users, isLoading } = useQuery({
    queryKey: ['users'],
    queryFn: async () => {
      const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/users');
      return res.json();
    },
  });

  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>; // Won't show on initial load!
  return <ul>{users?.map((u: any) => <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>)}</ul>;
}
```

The data is fetched on the server, serialized via `dehydrate`, and hydrated on the client. Subsequent navigations use TanStack Query's client-side caching and refetching. Create a new `QueryClient` per request in Server Components to avoid sharing state between users.

In Next.js, `redirect()` works by throwing a special error (NEXT_REDIRECT). If you call `redirect()` inside a try/catch, it gets caught and the redirect silently fails.

```tsx
// BAD — redirect is caught by try/catch
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  try {
    await db.insert(posts).values({ title: formData.get('title') });
    revalidatePath('/posts');
    redirect('/posts'); // This throws NEXT_REDIRECT, caught below!
  } catch (e) {
    return { error: 'Something went wrong' }; // Swallows the redirect
  }
}

// GOOD — redirect outside try/catch
'use server';
export async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  let success = false;
  try {
    await db.insert(posts).values({ title: formData.get('title') });
    success = true;
  } catch (e) {
    return { error: 'Something went wrong' };
  }

  if (success) {
    revalidatePath('/posts');
    redirect('/posts');
  }
}
```

Alternatively, you can re-throw the redirect error by checking `isRedirectError(e)` from `next/dist/client/components/redirect`. This applies to `notFound()` as well, which uses the same throw-based mechanism. This is one of the most common Server Action bugs in Next.js.

Route segment configuration lets you control rendering, caching, and runtime behavior at the page or layout level using exported constants.

```tsx
// app/dashboard/page.tsx

// Force dynamic rendering (no caching)
export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';

// Or force static rendering (build-time only)
export const dynamic = 'force-static';

// Set revalidation interval (ISR)
export const revalidate = 3600; // Revalidate every hour

// Choose runtime
export const runtime = 'edge'; // or 'nodejs' (default)

// Set max execution time (seconds)
export const maxDuration = 30;

// Control which dynamic params are allowed
export const dynamicParams = true; // false = return 404 for unknown params

// Generate static params for dynamic routes
export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const posts = await db.query.posts.findMany({ columns: { slug: true } });
  return posts.map((post) => ({ slug: post.slug }));
}

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const data = await fetchDashboardData();
  return <Dashboard data={data} />;
}
```

These exports are per-segment, not global. A layout's config applies to all pages in that segment. `dynamic = 'force-dynamic'` is equivalent to `getServerSideProps` from Pages Router. `revalidate = 0` means no caching. These values can be combined with `generateStaticParams` for hybrid static/dynamic rendering.

Error message: `Error: Invariant: headers() expects to have requestAsyncStorage, none available.` or similar errors for `cookies()`, `redirect()`, `notFound()`.

This error occurs when you call request-scoped functions outside of a request context — typically in module-level code, `generateStaticParams`, or during build time.

```tsx
// BAD — called at module level (outside request context)
import { headers } from 'next/headers';
const headersList = headers(); // ERROR!

export default function Page() {
  return <div>...</div>;
}

// BAD — called in generateStaticParams
export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const cookieStore = cookies(); // ERROR! No request context here
  return [{ slug: 'hello' }];
}

// GOOD — called inside the component function body
export default async function Page() {
  const headersList = await headers();
  const cookieStore = await cookies();
  const userAgent = headersList.get('user-agent');
  return <div>{userAgent}</div>;
}
```

In Next.js 15, `headers()` and `cookies()` are now async and return Promises. You must `await` them. These functions only work during server-side rendering of a request — they cannot be called during static generation, in `generateStaticParams`, or at the top level of a module. If you need header data in a statically generated page, pass it through middleware headers.

Optimistic updates in TanStack Query let you update the UI immediately while the mutation runs in the background, with automatic rollback on failure.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useMutation, useQueryClient } from '@tanstack/react-query';

export function useToggleTodo() {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient();

  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: async (todoId: string) => {
      const res = await fetch(`/api/todos/${todoId}/toggle`, { method: 'PATCH' });
      if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to toggle');
      return res.json();
    },
    onMutate: async (todoId) => {
      // Cancel outgoing refetches
      await queryClient.cancelQueries({ queryKey: ['todos'] });

      // Snapshot previous value for rollback
      const previousTodos = queryClient.getQueryData<Todo[]>(['todos']);

      // Optimistically update
      queryClient.setQueryData<Todo[]>(['todos'], (old) =>
        old?.map((todo) =>
          todo.id === todoId ? { ...todo, completed: !todo.completed } : todo
        )
      );

      return { previousTodos };
    },
    onError: (_err, _todoId, context) => {
      // Rollback on error
      queryClient.setQueryData(['todos'], context?.previousTodos);
    },
    onSettled: () => {
      // Always refetch to ensure consistency
      queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['todos'] });
    },
  });
}
```

The pattern is: cancel queries, snapshot, update optimistically, rollback on error, refetch on settle. The `context` returned from `onMutate` is passed to `onError` and `onSettled`. This works with any data shape — just adjust the `setQueryData` logic.

Intercepting routes let you show a route as a modal while keeping the URL updated. When the user navigates directly to the URL, they see the full page.

```
app/
  photos/
    [id]/
      page.tsx          # Full photo page (direct navigation)
  @modal/
    (.)photos/[id]/
      page.tsx          # Intercepted: shows as modal
      default.tsx
  layout.tsx
  default.tsx
```

```tsx
// app/layout.tsx
export default function RootLayout({
  children,
  modal,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  modal: React.ReactNode;
}) {
  return (
    <html><body>
      {children}
      {modal}
    </body></html>
  );
}

// app/@modal/(.)photos/[id]/page.tsx
import { Modal } from '@/components/Modal';

export default async function PhotoModal({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const photo = await getPhoto(id);
  return (
    <Modal>
      <img src={photo.url} alt={photo.title} />
    </Modal>
  );
}

// app/@modal/default.tsx
export default function Default() {
  return null; // No modal by default
}
```

The `(.)` prefix means intercept at the same level. Use `(..)` for one level up, `(..)(..)` for two levels up, or `(...)` for root level. The `default.tsx` file is crucial — without it, parallel slots that don't match the current URL will 404.

Server Actions don't have to be used with forms. In React 19, you can call them directly from event handlers using `useTransition` for loading states.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useTransition } from 'react';
import { deletePost, togglePublished } from '@/app/actions';

export function PostActions({ postId }: { postId: string }) {
  const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

  function handleDelete() {
    if (!confirm('Delete this post?')) return;
    startTransition(async () => {
      await deletePost(postId);
    });
  }

  function handleToggle() {
    startTransition(async () => {
      await togglePublished(postId);
    });
  }

  return (
    <div className="flex gap-2">
      <button onClick={handleToggle} disabled={isPending}>
        {isPending ? 'Updating...' : 'Toggle Published'}
      </button>
      <button onClick={handleDelete} disabled={isPending} className="text-red-600">
        {isPending ? 'Deleting...' : 'Delete'}
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Wrapping in `startTransition` marks the update as non-urgent, so the UI stays responsive. The `isPending` flag lets you show loading states. This pattern is ideal for buttons, toggles, and delete actions that aren't part of a form. The Server Action handles revalidation on the server side.

Error message: `Error: Objects are not valid as a React child (found: [object Promise]). If you meant to render a collection of children, use an array instead.`

This usually happens when you forget to `await` an async operation in a Server Component, or when you try to render an object directly.

```tsx
// BAD — forgot to await
export default function Page() {
  const data = fetch('https://api.example.com/data'); // Missing await!
  return <div>{data}</div>; // data is a Promise, not the resolved value
}

// BAD — rendering an object
export default async function Page() {
  const user = await getUser();
  return <div>{user}</div>; // user is { name: '...', email: '...' }
}

// FIX — await and render specific fields
export default async function Page() {
  const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
  const json = await data.json();
  return <div>{json.title}</div>;
}

// FIX — if in Client Component, use Suspense
'use client';
import { use } from 'react';

export function UserName({ userPromise }: { userPromise: Promise<User> }) {
  const user = use(userPromise);
  return <span>{user.name}</span>;
}
```

Also triggered by rendering `Date` objects (`{new Date()}` should be `{new Date().toLocaleDateString()}`), or passing a Server Component without async/await when it returns a Promise.

Using Zustand's `persist` middleware with Next.js causes a hydration mismatch because the server renders with the initial state while the client hydrates with localStorage state.

```tsx
// The problem: server renders count=0, client hydrates with count=5 from localStorage
const useStore = create(
  persist(
    (set) => ({ count: 0, increment: () => set((s) => ({ count: s.count + 1 })) }),
    { name: 'counter' }
  )
);

// FIX 1: Use onRehydrateStorage + skip rendering until hydrated
'use client';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

export function Counter() {
  const [hydrated, setHydrated] = useState(false);
  const count = useStore((s) => s.count);

  useEffect(() => {
    setHydrated(true);
  }, []);

  if (!hydrated) return <span>0</span>; // Match server output
  return <span>{count}</span>;
}

// FIX 2: Use Zustand's built-in hydration check
import { useStore } from './store';

export function Counter() {
  const count = useStore((s) => s.count);
  const hasHydrated = useStore.persist.hasHydrated();

  // Use suppressHydrationWarning on the element
  return <span suppressHydrationWarning>{hasHydrated ? count : 0}</span>;
}
```

The root cause is that localStorage is not available on the server. The `persist` middleware defaults to the initial state during SSR, then rehydrates with stored values on the client. Either delay rendering until hydration is complete, or use `suppressHydrationWarning` on specific elements.

Next.js App Router supports streaming by default. Use `<Suspense>` boundaries to stream in parts of the page as they become ready, without blocking the entire page on the slowest data fetch.

```tsx
// app/dashboard/page.tsx
import { Suspense } from 'react';

export default function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>
      {/* This renders immediately */}
      <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading stats...</p>}>
        <SlowStats /> {/* Streams in when ready */}
      </Suspense>
      <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading chart...</p>}>
        <SlowChart /> {/* Streams in independently */}
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}

async function SlowStats() {
  const stats = await fetch('https://api.example.com/stats', {
    cache: 'no-store',
  }).then((r) => r.json());
  return (
    <div className="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      <StatCard label="Users" value={stats.users} />
      <StatCard label="Revenue" value={stats.revenue} />
      <StatCard label="Orders" value={stats.orders} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

The page shell and any synchronous content render instantly. Each `<Suspense>` boundary streams its content as the async Server Component resolves. Components stream independently — `SlowChart` doesn't wait for `SlowStats`. This dramatically improves perceived performance. The `loading.tsx` file is just syntactic sugar for wrapping a page in `<Suspense>`. Use multiple boundaries for granular streaming.

Server Components and Client Components live in different environments. You cannot share state directly — but there are several patterns.

```tsx
// Pattern 1: Pass server data as props
// app/page.tsx (Server Component)
import { ClientDashboard } from './ClientDashboard';

export default async function Page() {
  const config = await getConfig(); // Server-side fetch
  return <ClientDashboard initialConfig={config} />;
}

// Pattern 2: URL state with searchParams
// app/products/page.tsx
export default async function ProductsPage({
  searchParams,
}: {
  searchParams: Promise<{ category?: string; sort?: string }>;
}) {
  const { category, sort } = await searchParams;
  const products = await getProducts({ category, sort });
  return <ProductGrid products={products} />;
}

// Client component updates URL:
'use client';
import { useRouter, useSearchParams } from 'next/navigation';

export function FilterBar() {
  const router = useRouter();
  const searchParams = useSearchParams();

  function setCategory(cat: string) {
    const params = new URLSearchParams(searchParams.toString());
    params.set('category', cat);
    router.push(`?${params.toString()}`);
  }

  return <select onChange={(e) => setCategory(e.target.value)}>...</select>;
}
```

Pattern 1 is for one-time data flow. Pattern 2 uses the URL as shared state — the Client Component updates the URL, which triggers a Server Component re-render with new `searchParams`. This is the recommended approach for filters, search, and pagination in the App Router.

When using `unstable_cache` (or the newer `'use cache'` directive), variables from the closure are NOT included in the cache key. This can lead to stale data.

```tsx
// BAD — userId is captured by closure but not in cache key
export async function getUserPosts(userId: string) {
  const getCachedPosts = unstable_cache(
    async () => {
      return db.query.posts.findMany({
        where: eq(posts.authorId, userId), // userId from closure!
      });
    },
    ['user-posts'], // Cache key doesn't include userId!
    { revalidate: 3600 }
  );
  return getCachedPosts();
}
// Result: All users get the same cached posts from the first call

// GOOD — include userId in the cache key
export async function getUserPosts(userId: string) {
  const getCachedPosts = unstable_cache(
    async () => {
      return db.query.posts.findMany({
        where: eq(posts.authorId, userId),
      });
    },
    [`user-posts-${userId}`], // userId in cache key
    { revalidate: 3600, tags: [`user-${userId}-posts`] }
  );
  return getCachedPosts();
}
```

Alternatively, pass dynamic values as arguments to the cached function instead of capturing them from the closure. Arguments ARE included in the cache key automatically. This is a subtle bug because the cached function works correctly on the first call — the issue only appears when a different user hits the same cache.

The recommended approach for using Zustand with Next.js App Router avoids hydration mismatches by creating the store per-request on the server and sharing it via context.

```tsx
// stores/counter-store.ts
import { createStore } from 'zustand';

export type CounterState = { count: number };
export type CounterActions = { increment: () => void; decrement: () => void };
export type CounterStore = CounterState & CounterActions;

export const createCounterStore = (initState: CounterState = { count: 0 }) =>
  createStore<CounterStore>()((set) => ({
    ...initState,
    increment: () => set((s) => ({ count: s.count + 1 })),
    decrement: () => set((s) => ({ count: s.count - 1 })),
  }));

// providers/counter-provider.tsx
'use client';
import { createContext, useContext, useRef } from 'react';
import { useStore } from 'zustand';
import { createCounterStore, type CounterStore } from '@/stores/counter-store';

type CounterStoreApi = ReturnType<typeof createCounterStore>;
const CounterCtx = createContext<CounterStoreApi | null>(null);

export function CounterProvider({ children, initialCount }: { children: React.ReactNode; initialCount: number }) {
  const storeRef = useRef<CounterStoreApi | null>(null);
  if (!storeRef.current) {
    storeRef.current = createCounterStore({ count: initialCount });
  }
  return <CounterCtx.Provider value={storeRef.current}>{children}</CounterCtx.Provider>;
}

export function useCounterStore<T>(selector: (s: CounterStore) => T): T {
  const store = useContext(CounterCtx);
  if (!store) throw new Error('useCounterStore must be used within CounterProvider');
  return useStore(store, selector);
}
```

The Server Component passes `initialCount` from the database. The store is created once per provider mount with `useRef`, matching the server-rendered output. This is Zustand's officially recommended pattern for Next.js.

Error message: `Error: useSearchParams() should be wrapped in a suspense boundary at page "/...". Read more: https://nextjs.org/docs/messages/missing-suspense-with-csr-bailout`

In Next.js 14+, using `useSearchParams()` in a Client Component without a `<Suspense>` boundary causes this error during static generation.

```tsx
// BAD — triggers the error
'use client';
import { useSearchParams } from 'next/navigation';

export default function SearchPage() {
  const searchParams = useSearchParams(); // Error!
  return <p>Query: {searchParams.get('q')}</p>;
}

// FIX 1 — wrap in Suspense
import { Suspense } from 'react';

export default function SearchPage() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<p>Loading...</p>}>
      <SearchContent />
    </Suspense>
  );
}

function SearchContent() {
  const searchParams = useSearchParams();
  return <p>Query: {searchParams.get('q')}</p>;
}

// FIX 2 — if the whole page needs searchParams, opt out of static rendering
export const dynamic = 'force-dynamic';
```

`useSearchParams()` causes the page to bail out of static generation because search params are only known at request time. Wrapping in `<Suspense>` lets Next.js statically render the page shell and hydrate the search params on the client. This is the recommended approach for search/filter pages.

After a successful Server Action, you often want to reset the form. React 19 makes this straightforward with `useRef` and `useActionState`.

```tsx
'use client';
import { useRef, useEffect } from 'react';
import { useActionState } from 'react';
import { addComment } from '@/app/actions';

type State = { success: boolean; error?: string };

export function CommentForm({ postId }: { postId: string }) {
  const formRef = useRef<HTMLFormElement>(null);

  const addCommentWithId = addComment.bind(null, postId);
  const [state, formAction, isPending] = useActionState(
    addCommentWithId,
    { success: false }
  );

  useEffect(() => {
    if (state.success) {
      formRef.current?.reset();
    }
  }, [state]);

  return (
    <form ref={formRef} action={formAction}>
      <textarea
        name="content"
        placeholder="Write a comment..."
        required
        rows={3}
        className="w-full rounded border p-2"
      />
      {state.error && <p className="text-red-500 text-sm">{state.error}</p>}
      <button
        type="submit"
        disabled={isPending}
        className="mt-2 rounded bg-blue-600 px-4 py-2 text-white"
      >
        {isPending ? 'Posting...' : 'Post Comment'}
      </button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

The `bind` pattern passes the `postId` as the first argument to the Server Action, keeping it out of the form data. The `useEffect` watches for `state.success` to reset the form. An alternative approach is to use a `key` prop on the form that changes on success, forcing React to remount it.
